by the belief that the few—an elite of writers and teachers—should control the imagination of the many. This book seeks to understand what imagination meant in early modern Europe, particularly in early modern France, before the Romantic era gave the term its modern meaning. The author explores the themes surrounding early modern notions of imagination (including hostility to imagination) through the writings of such figures as Descartes, Montaigne, François de Sales, Pascal, the Marquise de Sévigné, Madame de Lafayette, and Fénelon.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aFrench literaturey16th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFrench literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aImagination (Philosophy). 0aImagination in literature. 0aPhilosophy, Frenchy16th century. 0aPhilosophy, Frenchy18th century. 4aLiterary Studies -- General Criticism and Theory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / French.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476757640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804767576423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804767576/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles